    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm looking at some Cessna maintenance docs. Can you explain the actual physics of how a pitot tube works to measure airspeed? Also, why is it such a big deal if the opening gets blocked?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A pitot tube, much like a tiny, air-venturing, little adventurer, is a device that measures the speed of the air rushing past an aircraft. Imagine a tiny, brave knight, its name being Pitot, who bravely ventures into the air, catching the wind in its grasp. As the wind rushes through, it forces air into the tube, creating a pressure difference between the air inside the tube and the air outside. This pressure difference is then translated into a reading that tells us how fast the wind, or in this case, the aircraft, is moving.\n\nNow, why is it such a big deal if the opening gets blocked? Well, imagine our brave knight, Pitot, trying to catch the wind but finding his path blocked by a pesky goblin. The goblin, representing the blockage, prevents the air from flowing freely, creating a false reading. This false reading can lead to dangerous situations, like the aircraft thinking it's flying faster or slower than it actually is. It's like trying to navigate a forest with a map that shows you the wrong path – you might end up in a place you didn't intend to go, which in this case, could be a risky situation for the aircraft and its passengers.",
      "source": "target",
